content.name: High Notes Music Lessons
content.description:
High Notes Music Lessons. Exciting tailor-made music lessons in Amersham for children and adults.

An Introduction to Music (from 3 years)
General Music Lessons (from 5 years)
Private Piano Lessons (from 5 years)

Every 2 years I hold a concert with my pupils. March 2020 was our fifth concert. We showcase our talents as 'musicians' whilst playing within our comfort zones. As some of my students come for general music lessons, these are not piano concerts but music concerts featuring a wide variety of instruments.

Those participating are involved in three performances: a solo, an ensemble featuring everyone, plus a small group piece a duet, trio, quartet, or quintet. There is no age limit for those playing in the concerts with past events involving children from 3 to 14 years old, as well as grown-up pupils and of course, myself.

Please check the website or contact me for further details.

survey_answers.question: How do you involve parents and how can I get involved?
survey_answers.answer: We welcome parents into our setting to discuss their child's progress and any concerns they have. We also have regular parent events, for example dad's breakfast, mum's breakfast, reading sessions. Parents can request a meeting with their child's key person, the Principal or Deputy Principal at any time. We use Blossom to share regular observations and photographs about a child's learning journey. We also encourage parents to use the Blossom App to share news and activities their child has been enjoying at home. To support the children's learning at home we also share videos of Montessori activities which can be replicated at home.

survey_answers.question: How will you share information with me about my child’s progress? What is additional for children with SEND?
survey_answers.answer: The above opportunities are available for all parents, carers and family members. In addition to this we welcome more frequent opportunities to work with parents of children with SEND. We offer regular meetings, at least half termly which is when we would discuss "Assess, Plan, Do Review" plans for each child with SEND and regularly discuss outcomes with parents. Should other professional need to be involved such as Speech and Language therapists, Occupational Therapists, Health Visitors or Paediatricians we have close links with them and will hold meetings and telephone consultations as required.

survey_answers.question: How accessible is the environment (indoors and outdoors)?
survey_answers.answer: Our indoor environment has been adapted to be wheelchair accessible. This includes a disabled toilet. Access to the main building is via a slope and access to the court can be made via a ramp.  Our equipment is adjustable and we have a range of chairs to suit less physically able children. We audit our activities for suitability. We use a visual timetable to support all children with the classroom routine and visual prompts to aid communication.

survey_answers.question: How can children and young people with SEND and their families start to use your service or activity?
survey_answers.answer:
We understand each child's transition is individual to them. We work with the local schools and parents to ensure this is as smooth as possible. We offer a range of options including home visits, frequent settling in sessions, shortened sessions and social stories to support the child.
When the child is moving on to Primary school we offer accompanied transition visits to their next school and we invite future teachers to our school to meet the child. (Covid permitting). We also have a Time to Say Goodbye booklet to assist parents in preparing their child for the next steps

survey_answers.question: What future plans do you have for developing your SEND provision?
survey_answers.answer: We regularly review our training focus to ensure all staff's skills in supporting children  with SEN are kept up to date

content.name: High Wycombe Chair Making Museum CIC
content.description:
Visit our Chair Making Museum CIC at Kraft Village in High Wycombe.

We are now a CIC company. Wycombe has a wonderful chair making heritage, we made 4,700 chairs a day here in 1875. Our Museum tour explains how the Bodgers in the local Beech woods cut and turned the round parts for the chairs, the Bench men that made the other chair parts and Framers that assembled the Windsor chairs. We include a demonstration of rounding a billet on the shave horse and show how a chair leg is turned on the pole and treadle lathes. Besides the various old tools, we also have a display of  chairs and provide an explanation of the history and different types of Windsor chairs.   
  
Kraft Village also has a contemporary art gallery, craft gift shop and Kraftinwood wood-turning workshop, enquire about wood-turning lessons from Robert an RPT registered turner supported by the Worshipful Company of Turners.

content.name: Wycombe Homeless Connection: Housing Legal Clinic
content.description:
We run a free housing clinic for people across Buckinghamshire who are homeless or at risk of homelessness who may need legal advice or to access legal aid. 

Are you building up rent arrears, being threatened with eviction, struggling with housing benefits, experiencing anti-social behaviour or harassment, living in overcrowded, unsuitable or unsafe accommodation or in any situation that means you are worried about losing your home? We can help you. 

When you get in touch, a member of our team will ask questions about your situation and help you work out what your options are. 

We can help you in our drop-in support centre, over the phone, by email, by video conference and can arrange to see you by appointment. Let us know what works for you.

organisation.name: Wycombe Homeless Connection
organisation.description:
This service has temporarily been moved to a telephone helpline during the Coronavirus pandemic - 01494 447699 - please call between 10am to 4pm Mondays to Fridays for assistance.  
We help people who are homeless or at risk of homelessness by providing advice and support.  We can also assist with emergency food, clothing and bedding.
In addition to this, we also work to find accommodation for people who are homeless, we work with the Wycombe Rent Deposit Guarantee Scheme to find private rented accommodation, we can assist clients to register and bid on Bucks Home Choice for social housing and we can assist in making applications to hostels such as the Old Tea Warehouse and the YMCA, in some cases, we can also offer some financial assistance for the costs of moving into accommodation. 
We also help people who are at risk of homelessness to try to help them avoid being evicted. This includes housing legal clinics where clients can see a legal aid solicitor for free. 
We help people to deal with some of the negative effects of homelessness, find housing and help people who are at risk of being evicted avoid it or find alternative accommodation.

content.name: Hyde Heath Infant School
content.description:
Mixed-gender primary school in Hyde Heath, Amersham for 5 to 7-year-olds.

Hyde Heath is an Infant School for children aged four to seven years, which serves Hyde Heath Village and the surrounding district (Chesham, Amersham and Great Missenden).

We believe that Hyde Heath Infant School is a very special place to be. We pride ourselves on our inspiring teaching; creative curriculum and a caring ethos, and we encourage the highest standards of behaviour and achievement. We aim to develop the ‘whole’ child in a secure and purposeful environment where all the children feel valued and respected. Small class sizes mean teachers are able to get to know the children very well and support them as they develop into confident and happy learners.

We recognise that children benefit enormously when parents and teachers work together. Therefore we encourage close partnerships between home and school and keep you well informed about the progress of your children.

content.name: Curious Investigators (Thursday 6 April)
content.description:
An interactive engineering adventure for young scientists.

Scribble and Clipboard have a job to do: sort the recycling. But Scribble keeps finding new things to investigate. When she discovers a mysterious egg hidden in the rubbish, the pair need the audience’s help to rescue an unborn chick.

Can we save a mysterious egg from a smashing? And what will we discover along the way? Curious Investigatorsis a cracking adventure created in collaboration with engineering experts from Lancaster University: a delightfully surprising, highly visual show for 3 to 7-year-olds and their grown-ups.

This brand-new family show has been hatched by One Tenth Human, commissioned by Big Imaginations and supported by Arts Council England.

content.name: Easter Egg-Stravaganza Special Event (Saturday 8 April)
content.description:
A day full of family fun with lots to do including:

1:30pm – A special show from the Magical Story Elves – Blossom the Easter fairy is in fairy training and accidentally loses all of the Easter Eggs while practising her magic. The eggs have been scattered around to a variety of different dimensions including the hometown of a famous spider superhero and well-known princess. Can you help The Easter Fairy solve the clues and hunt for the lost eggs before the Easter Bunny returns to find them missing.

Take part in the 40 min interactive show including dancing, bubble catching, magic, party dances and much more. Followed by meet and greet with the characters, photo opportunities and a balloon model for each child.

Easter bonnet making drop-in workshops

Easter bonnet parade around the garden with prizes for the most creative.

Bring a picnic and rug to enjoy in our beautiful Victorian walled garden or purchase refreshments from the cafe. We recommend you arrive promptly to ensure you don’t miss any of the activities.

 Cost: £8.50 per child for the day (designed for children up to 10 years of age but all welcome. Under 3s and accompanying adults free)

local_offer.description:
Our SEN policy and information report aims:

To identify, at the earliest possible opportunity, barriers to learning and participation for pupils with SEND.
Help pupils develop their personalities, skills and abilities
Provide appropriate teaching which makes learning challenging and enjoyable.
Provide equality of educational opportunity.

As a whole Wooburn Green Primary has high expectations academically and we are determined to develop our children as well-round individuals by providing the highest quality daily experience.
Wooburn Green Primary SEN policy has been developed to:

Ensure that the diverse needs of all children, whatever their learning difficulty, are provided for, their barriers to learning minimized, they have equal opportunities to participate in the full curriculum of the school, and their successes are equally celebrated.
Ensure the implementation of Government and subsidiary Local Authority (LA) Guidance surrounding the SEND Code of Practice 0-25 (June 2014).
Ensure best practice, based on past practice and new guidelines, is applied consistently.
Inform parents/carers how SEN provision is organised at school, how it is identified, managed, and provided for, how educational plans co-ordinate with any Health/Social care provision and how this supports their child’s development.
Inform all parties how SEN provision works collaboratively – Child, Parents, Teachers, SENDCo and other professionals, and how concerns and issues will be managed.

content.name: Ambitious College
content.description:
We are London’s first specialist day college for children and young people with complex autism. 

At Ambitious College we offer young people specialist education and support and provide the vocational and community-based opportunities they need to make a successful transition to an active life in their community, including partnerships with local employers and services. 

Our co-located approach enables us to extend our curriculum significantly and offer learners a wide range of mainstream vocational learning, social opportunities and work experience. 

Our learners are at the heart of everything we do and their curriculum is highly personalised to help them achieve their goals. Within the curriculum, we embed functional literacy and numeracy, positive behaviour support, communication skills development and ICT skills development. 

We’re here to support young people with autism to achieve the life they want. 

To do this we follow the four pathways developed by Preparing for Adulthood:

Vocational Learning
Independent Living
Better Health
Friends, Relationships and Community

Learners, where there is an assessed need for it, have one to one support provided. The learner is at the centre of their study programme. Where possible they set and agree on their own learning targets or this is done involving their circles of support. 

There are monthly and annual learner reviews of progress that are set up and facilitated with the full input of the learner and to which parents and any other relevant parties attend to review and reset goals.

The curriculum is delivered by our very skilled and friendly staff. Staff are trained in a variety of communication methods including PECS, and Makaton. They also communicate in print and use iPads and assistive technologies where appropriate. 

Our curriculum is delivered through a trans-disciplinary team consisting of:

Qualified Teacher(s): plan and deliver sessions around the four Preparing for Adulthood pathways

Speech and Language Therapist(s): support learners to develop their communication and social interaction skills

Occupational Therapist(s): help learners to manage sensory issues and develop functional life skills

Behavioural Analyst(s): work with learners to overcome behavioural issues which could create barriers to learning

Employment specialist(s): support learners to develop vocational skills and access work experience

Learning and Behaviour Specialist(s): work with learners to access their person-centred curriculum and mainstream and community provision We know with the right support and opportunities, children and young people with autism can learn, thrive and achieve.

Cost by arrangement. Our learners are funded by local authorities, usually from education budgets with some input from social care and/or health as best meets the young person’s needs. Personal budgets can be used for the service, though we are in the early stages of exploring this with families and local authorities.

Local authority, parents or self-referral.

organisation.name: Ambitious about Autism Training and Consultancy
organisation.description: We are a national charity for children and young people with autism; our vision is to make the ordinary possible.   Here at Ambitious about Autism we understand the importance training for both staff and parents. We believe through schools, post-16 settings and employment based training we can help children and young people with autism thrive and achieve their full potential. Our highly qualified trainers have a wealth of knowledge and experience designing and delivering training on topics including; education law, autism awareness, communication skills, PBS and handling difficult situations. Our clients include local schools looking to improve understanding of autism as well as international clients keen to learn best practice.  Choose from one of our courses or request a bespoke package where we design and deliver training to meet your individual needs and objectives. We can deliver any of our training courses as an INSET day on a date that suits you.  We can work with you to design and deliver bespoke training and consultancy to suit your requirements and we welcome opportunities to be creative.   We run trainings specifically aimed at parents. Where parents and carers can share experiences whilst gaining a more in depth knowledge about autism and different interventions or behavioural approaches
